* Compare the film adaptation to the original text, in story, characters and themes. Compare it to other film adaptations.
* Compose a nonsense poem or simple rhyme as a shape poem to fit an outline of one of the characters, either about them or from their point of view.
* Did children spot any of the actors M-^QreappearingM-^R as voices of the puppet characters in Wonderland? What did these fantasy characters have in common with their real life counterparts? Identify the common characteristics of animals and each child design an animal character to resemble themselves and write a description of them (clothing, habits, interests, favourite food).
* Discuss in groups what is known of the original text, mapping the main events and discussing the main characters. What might be difficult about adapting the book for the screen? Think in particular about what is M-^QrealM-^R and what is M-^QimaginaryM-^R, a central theme of the book. 
* Discuss the Victorian setting of the film. How do the costumes, horse-drawn carriages, behaviour of characters and other elements in the film compare with what is known of life in Victorian England? Find images of these examples and compare them with images from the film from the website listed in M-^QWeblinksM-^R, below.
* In Wonderland, by combining the actress who played Alice with oversize props, as with the M-^QDrink MeM-^R bottle, the filmmakers created the illusion is that she had actually shrunk to a few centimetres tall. Then, putting her among tiny props, as in The White RabbitM-^Rs house, she appears to grow to giant size. Pupils could design and create different size props (tiny chair, huge chair) and explore in-camera special effects, making a short animated film using stop-frame animation with a digital camera in which characters appear to grow and shrink like Alice.
* Read a chapter of the original text. Investigate it for word play, riddles, rhymes and M-^QnonsenseM-^R. In Wonderland, where language is turned upside down, anything is possible. Look at the text of the Mad HatterM-^Rs Tea Party in Chapter 7. Write a M-^QnormalM-^R dialogue between two characters and turn it into nonsense, thinking carefully about how meaning changes with structure, vocabulary and intent.
* Take no more than two pages from the original text and adapt it into a screenplay to be acted out. In screenplays, the charactersM-^R names are in capitals, the text is centred on the page, there are no speech marks and minimal direction for the actors. 
* The film was made in the late 1940s. Which parts of the set design seem M-^QmodernM-^R, and which seem more traditionally Victorian? Why do you think the filmmakers decided to include such diverse looking sets M-^V how do they help us to understand the story? Think about the room full of doors, the DuchessM-^Rs kitchen, the formal gardens, the tea party M-^V how do they compare to what we know from images of Victorian England?
* The inhabitants of Wonderland are all puppets in this film, filmed with stop-motion animation like the Wallace and Gromit films. The figures are photographed one frame at a time, with tiny movements made in between. When the film is played, the figures seem to move of their own accord. Compare TennielsM-^R illustrations in the original publication with the puppets and actors in the film. What has been changed? Do children prefer one or the other, and why? Children can design their own 3D models of the characters.
